\begin_layout Section
Money in the Neoclassical Framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The fact that there is only a single point of equilibrium (intersection)
 - doesn't mean that in real life the economy will always be there.
 There is a process of discovery by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

agents
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - when out of equilibrium, something is wrong and people correct their
 behavior.
 Assuming exogenous variable don't change, eventually equilibrium is reached.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In real life we don't know whether we are currently at the equilibrium,
 and not even where the equilibrium is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When analyzing a shock, one shall look at the goods market first, and only
 then handle the labor market.
 Understanding forces is more important than calculating real and precise
 numbers, because the aggregate result is anyway influenced by all the people
 and the behavior.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Different models might be useful in different situations, because they depend
 on different assumptions.
 Thus, they do not really 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

compete
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with each other in the sense of explaining reality (i.e example with flexible
 vs.
 rigid prices.
 Keynesian framework is more relevant in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rigid
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 case).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Keynesian Framework
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our core assumption here is price rigidity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the case when the price is constant, and the demand curve shifts
 left (downward).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If there was no rigidity (in the neoclassical framework), prices would obviously
 fall.
 But as they are rigid, prices will remain constant.
 Production will fall because the demand is lower (can't 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

force people to buy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 It will decrease by 
\series bold
more 
\series default
than if prices were flexible.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As long as the production capacity is higher than what people are willing
 to buy (the demand), it is irrelevant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume now that 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\overline{P}$
\end_inset

 and let's repeat 
