\begin_layout Section
The IS-LM Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Instead of equating the supply and the demand of good, we'll use 2 equations
 (curves) which solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 as functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=Y^{d}\left(\begin{array}{c}
\Omega\\
(+)
\end{array},\begin{array}{c}
r\\
(-)
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

IS
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (investment-saving) curve, which we already saw slopping down in the 
\begin_inset Formula $r-Y$
\end_inset

 plane.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For every single level of wealth there can be infinite points (depending
 on the interest rate) thus a second equation is needed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{M}{\overline{P}}=L\left(\begin{array}{c}
Y\\
(+)
\end{array},\begin{array}{c}
r\\
(-)
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset

That's the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

LM
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (liquidity-money market) curve.
 The money supply is taken as exogenous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider some point 
\begin_inset Formula $(r_{0},y_{0})$
\end_inset

 which is known to be on the curve, and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}>y_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 Given the same exogenous variables, what will happen to 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

? It has to increase as well (to keep 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{M}{\overline{P}}$
\end_inset

 at the same level).
 Eventually interest will have to rise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When everyone tries to invest (buy bonds) - the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

price
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 rises (i.e interest rate falls down).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lower levels of both production & interest levels are consistent - same
 regarding higher levels (from LM point of view).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When there is less production is the economy, people will earn less and
 generally want to buy less.
 But they can use their savings for increased consumption (these are two
 different things).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the money supply is increased (assume even distribution), obviously money
 demand must go up as well.
 If production level and interest rate are assumed to be the same, people
 must be willing in an equilibrium to hold more liquidity.
 Having 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}>M_{0}$
\end_inset

 it is not equilibrium anymore.
 Considering production level doesn't change, interest rate must fall.
 Alternatively, it is possible that interest rate remaing the same and productio
n increases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We saw here 2 different analyses: In order to see 
\begin_inset Formula $LM$
\end_inset

 curve going upward, we assume left side stays the same.
 When looking at an exogenous change, we look at the right side and try
 to find ways for the equilibrium to still hold (
\begin_inset Formula $Y\uparrow$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $r\downarrow$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Keynesian framework assumes rigid prices, which is usually not so realistic.
\end_layout

