\begin_layout Subsection
Increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As usual, we assume the economy is in some steady state [being in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Keynesian state
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bad
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 state - recession].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start at an equilibrium, where LM and IS curve intersect.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As usual, the first thing is to find out what does 
\series bold
not
\series default
 change - it's the IS curve in our case.
 There's new purchasing power in the economy, so for every level of interest
 a higher level of production will be needed, or given a constant level
 of production the interest rate will have to decrease.
 The central bank printed more money, and by doing so - the production increased
 [the most benifical part - what we're usually after], and the interest
 rate decreased [side-effect].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In most cases, when an economy enters a recession, if CB decides that it
 is because of lack of demand (which is usually the case), they lower the
 interest rate and wait until it increases the demand for goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes demand is not the problem, and decreasing the interest rate doesn't
 help.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Increase in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
People are optimistic and have positive expectations regarding the future.
 Expectations 
\series bold
actually matter
\series default
.
 The LM curve won't move, but the IS will shift right (people feel more
 wealthier and they want to purchase more, at every level of interest rate
 and every given level of prices).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
People do want to work less than before, but they alreay work so much less
 than that - so that the diference doesn't matter (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

they want to work until 16 instead of 17, but it doesn't matter because
 they work until noon
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There will be an increase both in production rate and interest rate.
 It is generally considered as a good thing to exit a recession.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
People can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

be convinced
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (by setting expectations) that the future will be better.
 That assumes that the problem was initially cause by demand - otherwise,
 the Keynesian framework is not the correct one to apply to this situation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, usually prices are assumed to be rigid in the short-term, and
 flexible in the long-term.
 Thus, the Keynesian framework is mostly appropriate for specific temporary
 problem, while the neoclassical one is more fit for the long-term.
 It is extremely important to identify the correct framework to use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Government
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Until this point we didn't introduce government at all, especially in the
 neoclassical framework (in the Keynesian framework the can only print money).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The government has very significant impact on the economy.
 In some countries 
\begin_inset Formula $>50\%$
\end_inset

 of the GDP is collected and redistributed by taxes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
G Government purchases - 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

public goods
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, which can't be charged directly because the whole population benefits
 from them (i.e army).
 We assume that the government doesn't directly produce, but it is involved
 in the economy by collecting taxes and spending them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
T Taxes - for simplicity are assumed to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lump sum
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - are considered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the best
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by economists
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
B Government Debt - Taxes are not the only way to finance spendings, but
 also by issuing debt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Government budget constraint:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G+(1+r)B_{-1}=T+B
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Spending + paying debt interest = Taxes + new debt.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is only 
\series bold
today
\series default
 constraint.
 We assume countries 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

live forever
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 What will happen at the next period?
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G_{+1}+(1+r)B=T_{+1}+B_{+1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bonds taken today have to be redeemed tomorrow, in a manner similar to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

current period
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We usually try to look at it in 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

present value
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+r)$
\end_inset

):
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{G_{+1}}{1+r}+B=\frac{T_{+1}}{1+r}+\frac{B_{+1}}{1+r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both years together:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G+\frac{G_{+1}}{1+r}+(1+r)B_{-1}=T+\frac{T_{+1}}{1+r}+\frac{B_{+1}}{1+r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Government intertemporal budget - generalization of the above equations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G+\frac{G_{+1}}{1+r}+\frac{G_{+2}}{(1+r)^{2}}+\cdots+(1+t)B_{-1}=T+\frac{T_{+1}}{1+r}+\frac{T_{+2}}{(1+r)^{2}}+\cdots
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The only exogenous variable here is 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{-1}$
\end_inset

 (assuming the government has discretion on how much to actually spend).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This simple exercies has huge implications, which are sadly usually misunderstoo
d.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Interpretation - the Ricardian equivalence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The government spending and taxes don't have to be equal in each and every
 period, but 
\series bold
eventually
\series default
 they do [we can 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

default
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, but debt can't be rolled forever - eventually it has to be paid].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adding the government to the neoclassical framework, we get consumption
 demand:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C^{d}=C^{d}\left(\begin{array}{c}
\Omega\\
(+)
\end{array},\begin{array}{c}
r\\
(-)
\end{array}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But now there is an additional part - future taxes:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Omega=\cdots-\left(G+\frac{G_{+1}}{1+r}+\cdots\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Total demang for goods:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y_{d}=C+G
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Temporary Increase in government purchases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the case when government decides to increase (
\series bold
only
\series default
 for this perios) purchases of goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even without telling that explicitly, it is obvious that taxes will rise.
 So, present value of taxes will increase.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume that productivity doesn't change.
 The demand curve shifts right, leading to increase in demand and in the
 interest rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Permanent increase in government purchases
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Government expenditure introduces an addition to demand.
 Building an airport 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

once
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 vs.
 doing it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

every year
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 have very different implications.
 It means a huge reduction of wealth, which takes effect from now and forever.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Considering the government wants to smooth the tax collection, it must be
 raised by the same amount (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta T=\Delta G$
\end_inset

) 
\series bold
in every period
\series default
, otherwise an interset will have to be paid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking at that from a household perspective.
 Consider an announcement of a sudden tax one-time decrease.
 The wealth does not depend on the taxes paid today! Government spending
 didn't decrease, so it will have to be funded eventually (it is only delayed),
 thus the only reasonable thing to do in such situation would be putting
 this sum in a savings account (the government will have to issue bonds
 for these messing taxes).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wealth depends on government expenditure, not on taxes (which are only
 a change in 
\series bold
scheduling
\series default
 the taxes).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Government expenditure moves the demand curve to the right by 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta G$
\end_inset

.
 As the wealth is less now, one needs to either reduce consumption or increase
 labor.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\series bold
only
\series default
 consumption is reduced (putting 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the entire burden
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of that additional tax on the consumption) - the demand will 
\series bold
go back
\series default
 by the same amount that the government has spent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another option is to have some combination of consuming less and working
 more.
 The actual final situation depends on the exact combination people will
 choose.
\end_layout

